{"title_page": "Matt Jardine", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| image            = Matt Jardine.jpg\n| name             = Matthew Alan Jardine\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_place      = Big Sur, California\n| origin           = \n| birth_date       = December 9, 1966 (age 53)\n| genre            = *[[rock and roll]], [[surf rock]], [[psychedelic rock]]\n| occupation       = Musician\n| instrument       = Vocals, percussion, guitar\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[The Beach Boys]], [[Al Jardine]], [[Brian Wilson]], [[Wilson Phillips]], California Saga\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Matthew Alan Jardine''' (born December 9th, 1966 in Big Sur, California) is an American musician, best known for his work as a vocalist and percussionist for [[the Beach Boys]] and [[Brian Wilson]]. He is the son of original Beach Boy [[Al Jardine]].\n\n==Biography==\nJardine is the son of longtime Beach Boys guitarist [[Al Jardine]]. His first major recording was at the age of 11 and was the narration of the Beach Boys' recording of   \"(I Saw Santa) Rockin' Around The Christmas Tree\" from the album ''Christmas with the Beach Boys''.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Jardine, alongside the other Beach Boys' children (the \"Adam\" referred to in the narration was his younger brother, Adam Jardine, age six), sang the background vocals on this song.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nDuring the 1980s, Jardine spent time on the road with the Beach Boys as a gopher to earn money.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} This led to an assistant road manager job in the summer of 1988, which he retained until Carl Wilson asked if he could play percussion onstage while continuing his other duties.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} During this tour Jardine was asked to sing background vocals on a part-time basis filling in for other vocalists in the band, whose voices had grown tired due to the band's year-round touring schedule.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1991, Jardine auditioned for the band and earned a spot in the band as a lead and falsetto vocalist, background singer and percussionist.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} He toured with the Beach Boys from 1990 through 1998, performing on three of their studio albums.  Jardine sang Brian Wilson's original falsetto vocals on tour; these songs included \"Warmth of the Sun\", \"Don't Worry Baby\", and \"Hushabye\".{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} He has appeared in nine Beach Boys' music videos and made numerous TV appearances. During the latter part of his time with the Beach Boys, Jardine also worked extensively with Mike Love's California Beach Band.  He also toured with Jan and Dean for numerous shows and events.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1998, Jardine was asked to perform with Brian Wilson on TNT's ''Front Row and Center'' as well as Farm Aid '98. Wilson was quoted as saying of Jardine in ''Billboard'' magazine, \"I hear him from behind the stage.  His voice is stronger than mine, and he can actually hit those high notes.\"{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nJardine later went on the road with Brian's daughters Carnie and Wendy Wilson and friend Chynna Phillips, the multi-platinum trio [[Wilson Phillips]], to help them promote their ''California'' album.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Carnie and Wendy were not only childhood friends but had also worked with Jardine and his father while touring as Alan Jardine's Family and Friends following their departure from the Beach Boys touring band in 1998.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Jardine has continued to tour with his father and the Surf City All-Stars. In 2014, he was asked to join the Brian Wilson touring band, replacing [[Jeff Foskett]]; he accepted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smileysmile.net/board/index.php/topic,17604.275.html |title=Rolling Stone \u2013 Beach Boys Play Tour \u2013 Jeff replaces Christian Love |publisher=Smileysmile.net |date= |accessdate=2014-05-26}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===The Beach Boys===\n*''[[M.I.U. Album]]'' (1978) \n*''[[Still Cruisin']]'' (1989)\n*''[[Summer in Paradise]]'' (1992)\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mattjardinemusic.com/bio.html |title=Bio \u2013 Matt Jardine |publisher=Mattjardinemusic.com |date=January 1, 1970 |accessdate=2014-05-26}}</ref>\n\n===Al Jardine===\n*''[[Live in Las Vegas (Al Jardine album)|Live in Las Vegas]]'' (2001)\n*''[[A Postcard from California]]'' (2010)\n\n===Brian Wilson===\n*''[[No Pier Pressure]]'' (2015)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jardine, Matt}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The Beach Boys backing band members]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=January 2016}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2014}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| image            = Matt Jardine.jpg\n| name             = Matthew Alan Jardine\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_place      = Big Sur, California\n| origin           = \n| birth_date       = December 9, 1966 (age 53)\n| genre            = *[[rock and roll]], [[surf rock]], [[psychadelic rock]]\n| occupation       = Musician\n| instrument       = Vocals, percussion, guitar\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[The Beach Boys]], [[Al Jardine]], [[Brian Wilson]], [[Wilson Phillips]], California Saga\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Matthew Alan Jardine''' (born December 9th, 1966 in Big Sur, California) is an American musician, best known for his work as a vocalist and percussionist for [[the Beach Boys]] and [[Brian Wilson]]. He is the son of original Beach Boy [[Al Jardine]].\n\n==Biography==\nJardine is the son of longtime Beach Boys guitarist [[Al Jardine]]. His first major recording was at the age of 11 and was the narration of the Beach Boys' recording of   \"(I Saw Santa) Rockin' Around The Christmas Tree\" from the album ''Christmas with the Beach Boys''.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Jardine, alongside the other Beach Boys' children (the \"Adam\" referred to in the narration was his younger brother, Adam Jardine, age six), sang the background vocals on this song.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nDuring the 1980s, Jardine spent time on the road with the Beach Boys as a gopher to earn money.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} This led to an assistant road manager job in the summer of 1988, which he retained until Carl Wilson asked if he could play percussion onstage while continuing his other duties.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} During this tour Jardine was asked to sing background vocals on a part-time basis filling in for other vocalists in the band, whose voices had grown tired due to the band's year-round touring schedule.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1991, Jardine auditioned for the band and earned a spot in the band as a lead and falsetto vocalist, background singer and percussionist.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} He toured with the Beach Boys from 1990 through 1998, performing on three of their studio albums.  Jardine sang Brian Wilson's original falsetto vocals on tour; these songs included \"Warmth of the Sun\", \"Don't Worry Baby\", and \"Hushabye\".{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} He has appeared in nine Beach Boys' music videos and made numerous TV appearances. During the latter part of his time with the Beach Boys, Jardine also worked extensively with Mike Love's California Beach Band.  He also toured with Jan and Dean for numerous shows and events.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nIn 1998, Jardine was asked to perform with Brian Wilson on TNT's ''Front Row and Center'' as well as Farm Aid '98. Wilson was quoted as saying of Jardine in ''Billboard'' magazine, \"I hear him from behind the stage.  His voice is stronger than mine, and he can actually hit those high notes.\"{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}}\n\nJardine later went on the road with Brian's daughters Carnie and Wendy Wilson and friend Chynna Phillips, the multi-platinum trio [[Wilson Phillips]], to help them promote their ''California'' album.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Carnie and Wendy were not only childhood friends but had also worked with Jardine and his father while touring as Alan Jardine's Family and Friends following their departure from the Beach Boys touring band in 1998.{{Citation needed|date=April 2020}} Jardine has continued to tour with his father and the Surf City All-Stars. In 2014, he was asked to join the Brian Wilson touring band, replacing [[Jeff Foskett]]; he accepted.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://smileysmile.net/board/index.php/topic,17604.275.html |title=Rolling Stone \u2013 Beach Boys Play Tour \u2013 Jeff replaces Christian Love |publisher=Smileysmile.net |date= |accessdate=2014-05-26}}</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===The Beach Boys===\n*''[[M.I.U. Album]]'' (1978) \n*''[[Still Cruisin']]'' (1989)\n*''[[Summer in Paradise]]'' (1992)\n<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mattjardinemusic.com/bio.html |title=Bio \u2013 Matt Jardine |publisher=Mattjardinemusic.com |date=January 1, 1970 |accessdate=2014-05-26}}</ref>\n\n===Al Jardine===\n*''[[Live in Las Vegas (Al Jardine album)|Live in Las Vegas]]'' (2001)\n*''[[A Postcard from California]]'' (2010)\n\n===Brian Wilson===\n*''[[No Pier Pressure]]'' (2015)\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Jardine, Matt}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The Beach Boys backing band members]]\n[[Category:1966 births]]\n", "name_user": "Mandarax", "label": "safe", "comment": "Fix typo", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Matt_Jardine"}
{"title_page": "Tocaima", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Tocaima\n| native_name             =\n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| settlement_type         = City and Municipality\n| image_skyline           = Iglesia Tocaima.jpg\n| image_alt               =\n| image_caption           =\n| image_flag              = Flag of Tocaima.svg\n| flag_alt                = Flag of Tocaima\n| image_seal              = \n| seal_alt                = \n| image_shield            = Escudo de Tocaima.svg\n| shield_alt              = \n| nickname                =\n| motto                   =\n| image_map               = Colombia - Cundinamarca - Tocaima.svg\n| map_alt                 =\n| map_caption             = Location of the town and municipality of Tocaima within [[Cundinamarca Department]]\n|pushpin_map              = Colombia\n|pushpin_mapsize          = 250\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location in Colombia\n| coordinates             = {{coord|4|30|N|74|40|W|region:CO_type:adm2nd_source:GNS-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           =\n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[Colombia]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Department (administrative division)|Department]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Cundinamarca Department|Cundinamarca]]\n| subdivision_type2       =\n| subdivision_name2       =\n| subdivision_type3       =\n| subdivision_name3       =\n| established_title       = Founded\n| established_date        = March 20, 1544\n| established_title2      = Destroyed\n| established_date2       = 1581\n| established_title3      = Re-founded\n| established_date3       = March 18, 1621\n| founder                 = [[Hern\u00e1n Venegas Carrillo]]\n| named_for               = Legendary warrior of the [[Guacana]] tribe\n| seat_type               = Municipal Seat\n| seat                    = Tocaima\n| government_footnotes    =\n| leader_party            =\n| leader_title            =\n| leader_name             =\n| total_type              = Tocaima (Municipality)\n| unit_pref               = Metric<!-- or US or UK -->\n| area_footnotes          =\n| area_total_km2          =\n| area_land_km2           =\n| area_water_km2          =\n| area_water_percent      =\n| area_note               =\n| elevation_footnotes     = <ref name=\"sa-handbook\">{{cite book|title=Colombia: physical features, natural resources, means of communication, manufactures and industrial development|series=South American handbooks|last=L\u00e9vine|first=V.|publisher=D. Appleton|location=New York|year=1920|page=180|oclc=6459630|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ZZt1AAAAMAAJ&lpg=PA180&ots=VwmDoDzmUa&pg=PA180#v=onepage&q&f=false|accessdate=2010-10-14}}</ref>\n| elevation_ft            = 1416\n| population_footnotes    = <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.statoids.com/yco.html|title=Municipalities of Colombia|work=Statoids|last=Law|first=Fwillim|date=2008-07-02|accessdate=2010-10-14}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wolframalpha.com/input/?i=tocaima%2C+colombia&a=*C.tocaima%2C+colombia-_*City-|title=Tocaima, Cundinamarca, Colombia|work=WolframAlpha|publisher=Wolfram Research|year=2010|accessdate=2010-10-14}}</ref>\n| population_total        = 13649\n| population_as_of        = Census 2018<ref name=\"Censo\">{{Cita web |url=https://sitios.dane.gov.co/cnpv/#!/ |title=Censo Nacional de Poblaci\u00f3n y Vivienda 2018|publisher=[[Departamento Administrativo Nacional de Estad\u00edstica |DANE]]|lang=es |access-date=25 April 2020}}</ref>\n| population_density_km2  = auto\n| population_demonym      =\n| population_note         =\n| population_blank1_title = \n| population_blank1       = \n| timezone1               = Western Caribbean\n| utc_offset1             = -05:00\n| timezone1_DST           =\n| utc_offset1_DST         =\n| postal_code_type        =\n| postal_code             =\n| area_code_type          =\n| area_code               = 83\n| iso_code                =\n| website                 = {{URL|tocaima-cundinamarca.gov.co}}\n| footnotes               =\n}}\n\n'''Tocaima''' ({{IPA-es|to\u02c8kajma}}) refers to both a city and a municipality in [[Cundinamarca Department|Cundinamarca]], [[Colombia]].\n\n==City==\nThe city of Tocaima was founded on March 20, 1544 by the Spanish explorer [[Hern\u00e1n Venegas Carrillo]]. This small city is most well known for being a warm [[Tourism|vacation]] site during [[religious holiday]]s, especially for college students from [[Bogot\u00e1]] and other surrounding areas.{{Citation needed|date=October 2010}}\n\nThe town is crossed by the [[Pati River]], which sometimes floods the town.\n\n===History===\nBefore Spanish colonization, the area was home to the [[Guacana]], an [[Amerindian]] tribe belonging to the [[Panche people|Panche]] Amerindian Nation. Tocaima was named in honor of a legendary warrior from this tribe, during the ruling period of the [[Cacique|Cacica]] Guacana.\n\nIt is believed{{By whom|date=November 2010}} that Tocaima is the only city in the [[Cundinamarca Department]] that presently has a royal title and [[coat of arms]] issued by the [[Spanish Monarchy]]. [[Charles V, Holy Roman Emperor|Charles V]] issued the royal title and coat of arms on February 7, 1549, in appreciation of the city's loyalty and fame for being a powerful and wealthy region.\n\nIn 1581, the city was completely destroyed by an exceptionally devastating flood of the Pati River. President [[Juan Buenaventura de Borja y Armendia|Juan de Borja]] sent Captain [[Martin de Ocampo]] to refound the city, which he did on March 18, 1621 by constructing the [[Convent]] of San Jacinto and its contiguous chapel.\n\nDuring the decolonization of Colombia from Spain in 1810, Tocaima was represented in the [[electoral college|electoral]] and [[constituent assembly|constitutional college]] by jurist [[Miguel de Tobar y Zerrato]] and Don [[Juan Salvador Rodriguez de Lago]]. The [[Cabildo (council)|Cabildo]], or colonial administrative council, was re-established that same year.\n\nThe new [[Constitution of Cundinamarca]], created in 1815, divided the nation into [[Canton (subnational entity)|cantons]], which provoked a confrontation between the Tocaima Canton and the neighboring Canton of [[La Mesa, Cundinamarca|La Mesa]]. In 1816, Spain re-conquered the colonies and subsequently repressed the newly created government.\n\nAfter finally defeating the Spanish in 1819, the colonists declared total independence from Spain and created the Republic of [[Gran Colombia]], which\u2014led by General [[Francisco de Paula Santander|Santander]] in 1822\u2014re-established the Tocaima Canton.\n\nIn 1906, Tocaima was notable for its gold and copper mines,<ref>{{cite encyclopedia\n  | encyclopedia = Lippincott's New Gazetteer: A complete pronouncing gazetteer or geographical dictionary of the world, containing the most recent and authentic information respecting the countries, cities, towns ... in every portion of the globe\n  | editor-last = Heilprin\n  | editor-first = Angelo\n  | editor2-last = Heilprin\n  | editor2-first = Louis\n  | title = Tocaima\n  | page = 1840\n  | volume = 2\n  | publisher = J. B. Lippincott\n  | location = Philadelphia\n  | asin = B0010K3YKW \n  | oclc = 1870625\n  | year = 1906\n  | accessdate = 2010-10-14\n  | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=5iA9AAAAYAAJ&lpg=PA1840&ots=lzBfurhPoL&pg=PA1840#v=onepage&q&f=false\n}}</ref>\nbut neither mineral was mined there by 1920.<ref name=\"sa-handbook\"/>\n\n{{Clear}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Municipalities cundinamarca department}}\n\n[[Category:Municipalities of Cundinamarca Department]]\n[[Category:Populated places in the Cundinamarca Department]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n<!-- See Template:Infobox settlement for additional fields and descriptions -->\n| name                    = Tocaima\n| native_name             =\n| native_name_lang        = <!-- ISO 639-2 code e.g. \"fr\" for French. If more than one, use {{lang}} instead -->\n| settlement_type         = City and Municipality\n| image_skyline           = Iglesia Tocaima.jpg\n| image_alt               =\n| image_caption           =\n| image_flag              = Flag of Tocaima.svg\n| flag_alt                = Flag of Tocaima\n| image_seal              = \n| seal_alt                = \n| image_shield            = Escudo de Tocaima.svg\n| shield_alt              = \n| nickname                =\n| motto                   =\n| image_map               = Colombia - Cundinamarca - Tocaima.svg\n| map_alt                 =\n| map_caption             = Location of the town and municipality of Tocaima within [[Cundinamarca Department]]\n|pushpin_map              = Colombia\n|pushpin_mapsize          = 250\n|pushpin_map_caption      = Location in Colombia\n| coordinates             = {{coord|4|30|N|74|40|W|region:CO_type:adm2nd_source:GNS-enwiki|display=inline,title}}\n| coor_pinpoint           =\n| coordinates_footnotes   =\n| subdivision_type        = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_name        = [[Colombia]]\n| subdivision_type1       = [[Department (administrative division)|Department]]\n| subdivision_name1       = [[Cundinamarca Department|Cundinamarca]]\n| subdivision_type2       =\n| subdivision_name2       =\n| subdivision_type3       =\n| subdivision_name3       =\n| established_title       = Founded\n| established_date        = March 20, 1544\n| established_title2      = Destroyed\n| established_date2       = 1581\n| established_title3      = Re-founded\n| established_date3       = March 18, 1621\n| founder                 = [[Hern\u00e1n Venegas Carrillo]]\n| named_for               = Legendary warrior of the [[Guacana]] tribe\n| seat_type               = Municipal Seat\n| seat                    = Tocaima\n| 