from India]]\n[[Category:Film directors from New York City]]\n[[Category:LGBT Muslims]]\n[[Category:LGBT American people of Asian descent]]\n[[Category:LGBT memoirists]]\n[[Category:American progressive Muslims]]\n[[Category:American Muslim activists]]\n[[Category:Indian Muslim activists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Indian Muslims]]\n", "name_user": "Danaparamita", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eEarly life:Added a space", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Parvez_Sharma"}
{"title_page": "Holobiont", "text_new": "\n\nA '''holobiont''' is an assemblage of a [[Host (biology)|host]] and the many other species living in or around it, which together form a discrete [[ecological unit]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/symbiosis-source-evolutionary-innovation|title=Symbiosis as a Source of Evolutionary Innovation|last=Margulis|first=Lynn|last2=Fester|first2=Ren\u00e9|date=|website=|publisher=MIT Press|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2016-08-12}}</ref> The components of a holobiont are individual species or [[Wiktionary:biont|bionts]], while the combined [[genome]] of all bionts is the [[Hologenome theory of evolution|hologenome]]. The concept of the holobiont was defined by [[Lynn Margulis|Dr. Lynn Margulis]] in her 1991 book ''Symbiosis as a Source of Evolutionary Innovation''<ref name=\":02\" />. Holobionts include the host, virome, microbiome, and other members, all of which contribute in some way to the function of the whole<ref name=\":4\">Bulgarelli, Davide, Klaus Schlaeppi, Stijn Spaepen, Emiel Ver Loren van Themaat, and Paul Schulze-Lefert. \u201cStructure and Functions of the Bacterial Microbiota of Plants.\u201d ''Annual Review of Plant Biology'' 64, no. 1 (2013): 807\u201338. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-arplant-050312-120106</nowiki>. </ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Vandenkoornhuyse|first=Philippe|last2=Quaiser|first2=Achim|last3=Duhamel|first3=Marie|last4=Le Van|first4=Amandine|last5=Dufresne|first5=Alexis|date=2015-06-01|title=The importance of the microbiome of the plant holobiont|journal=The New Phytologist|volume=206|issue=4|pages=1196\u20131206|doi=10.1111/nph.13312|issn=1469-8137|pmid=25655016}}</ref>. Well-studied holobionts include [[Coral|reef-building corals]] and humans<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":6\" />.\n\n== Definition ==\nA holobiont is a collection of species that are closely associated and have complex interactions, such as a plant species and the members of its [[Microbiota|microbiome]]<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":1\">S\u00e1nchez-Ca\u00f1izares, Carmen, Beatriz Jorr\u00edn, Philip S Poole, and Andrzej Tkacz. \u201cUnderstanding the Holobiont: The Interdependence of Plants and Their Microbiome.\u201d ''Current Opinion in Microbiology'', Mobile genetic elements and HGT in prokaryotes * Microbiota, 38 (August 1, 2017): 188\u201396. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1016/j.mib.2017.07.001</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1016%2Fj.mib.2017.07.001&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Understanding%20the%20holobiont%3A%20the%20interdependence%20of%20plants%20and%20their%20microbiome&rft.jtitle=Current%20Opinion%20in%20Microbiology&rft.stitle=Current%20Opinion%20in%20Microbiology&rft.volume=38&rft.aufirst=Carmen&rft.aulast=S%C3%A1nchez-Ca%C3%B1izares&rft.au=Carmen%20S%C3%A1nchez-Ca%C3%B1izares&rft.au=Beatriz%20Jorr%C3%ADn&rft.au=Philip%20S%20Poole&rft.au=Andrzej%20Tkacz&rft.date=2017-08-01&rft.pages=188-196&rft.spage=188&rft.epage=196&rft.issn=1369-5274&rft.language=en\"></span></ref>. Each species present in a holobiont is a biont, and the genomes of all bionts taken together are the hologenome, or the \"comprehensive gene system\" of the holobiont<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Bordenstein|first=Seth R.|last2=Theis|first2=Kevin R.|date=2015-08-18|title=Host Biology in Light of the Microbiome: Ten Principles of Holobionts and Hologenomes|journal=PLOS Biol|volume=13|issue=8|pages=e1002226|doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.1002226|issn=1545-7885|pmc=4540581|pmid=26284777}}</ref>. A holobiont typically includes a [[eukaryote]] [[Host (biology)|host]] and all of the [[Symbiosis|symbiotic]] [[Virus|viruses]], [[bacteria]], [[Fungus|fungi]], etc. that live on or inside it<ref name=\":1\" />.\n\n== Versus Superorganism ==\nHolobionts are distinct from [[Superorganism|superorganisms]]; superorganisms consist of many individuals, sometimes of the same species, and the term is commonly applied to [[eusocial]] insects<ref>Youle, Merry, Nancy Knowlton, Forest Rohwer, Jeffrey Gordon, and David A. Relman. \u201cSuperorganisms and Holobionts: Looking for a Term for the Functional Entity Formed by a Macrobe and Its Associated Symbiotic Microbes and Viruses? The Term Is \u2018Holobiont.\u2019\u201d ''Microbe Magazine'' 8, no. 4 (April 1, 2013): 152\u201353. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1128/microbe.8.152.1</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1128%2Fmicrobe.8.152.1&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Superorganisms%20and%20Holobionts%3A%20Looking%20for%20a%20term%20for%20the%20functional%20entity%20formed%20by%20a%20macrobe%20and%20its%20associated%20symbiotic%20microbes%20and%20viruses%3F%20The%20term%20is%20%E2%80%9Cholobiont%E2%80%9D&rft.jtitle=Microbe%20Magazine&rft.volume=8&rft.issue=4&rft.aufirst=Merry&rft.aulast=Youle&rft.au=Merry%20Youle&rft.au=Nancy%20Knowlton&rft.au=Forest%20Rohwer&rft.au=Jeffrey%20Gordon&rft.au=David%20A.%20Relman&rft.date=2013-04-01&rft.pages=152-153&rft.spage=152&rft.epage=153&rft.issn=1558-7452%2C%201558-7460&rft.language=en\"></span></ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/b29809198|title=The Social Insects, Their Origin and Evolution|last1=Wheeler|first1=WM|date=1928|publisher=Harcourt Brace}}</ref>. An [[ant colony]] can be described as a superorganism, whereas an individual ant and its associated bacteria, fungi, etc. are a holobiont<ref name=\":2\" />. However, there is still some controversy surrounding these terms, and they have been used interchangeably in some publications<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last1=Kramer|first1=Peter|last2=Bressan|first2=Paola|date=2015|title=Humans as superorganisms: How microbes, viruses, imprinted genes, and other selfish entities shape our behavior|journal=Perspectives on Psychological Science|volume=10|issue=4|pages=464\u2013481|doi=10.1177/1745691615583131|issn=1745-6916|pmid=26177948|url=https://zenodo.org/record/894598}} [https://zenodo.org/record/894598#.WdntKGKCw1h Free, full text].</ref>.\n\n== Components of the Holobiont ==\n\n=== Host ===\nThe host member of a holobiont is typically a multicellular [[eukaryote]], such as a plant or human<ref name=\":2\" />. Notable hosts that are well-studied include humans<ref>Guchte, Maarten van de, Herv\u00e9 M. Blotti\u00e8re, and Jo\u00ebl Dor\u00e9. \u201cHumans as Holobionts: Implications for Prevention and Therapy.\u201d ''Microbiome'' 6, no. 1 (December 2018): 81. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1186/s40168-018-0466-8</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1186%2Fs40168-018-0466-8&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Humans%20as%20holobionts%3A%20implications%20for%20prevention%20and%20therapy&rft.jtitle=Microbiome&rft.stitle=Microbiome&rft.volume=6&rft.issue=1&rft.aufirst=Maarten&rft.aulast=van%20de%20Guchte&rft.au=Maarten%20van%20de%20Guchte&rft.au=Herv%C3%A9%20M.%20Blotti%C3%A8re&rft.au=Jo%C3%ABl%20Dor%C3%A9&rft.date=2018-12&rft.pages=81&rft.issn=2049-2618&rft.language=en\"></span></ref>, corals<ref name=\":0\">Knowlton, Nancy, and Forest Rohwer. \u201cMultispecies Microbial Mutualisms on Coral Reefs: The Host as a Habitat.\u201d ''The American Naturalist'' 162, no. 4 Suppl (October 2003): S51-62. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1086/378684</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1086%2F378684&rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F14583857&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Multispecies%20microbial%20mutualisms%20on%20coral%20reefs%3A%20the%20host%20as%20a%20habitat&rft.jtitle=The%20American%20Naturalist&rft.stitle=Am.%20Nat.&rft.volume=162&rft.issue=4%20Suppl&rft.aufirst=Nancy&rft.aulast=Knowlton&rft.au=Nancy%20Knowlton&rft.au=Forest%20Rohwer&rft.date=2003-10&rft.pages=S51-62&rft.spage=S51&rft.epage=62&rft.issn=0003-0147&rft.language=eng\"></span></ref>,  and pine trees<ref>Hacquard, St\u00e9phane, and Christopher W. Schadt. \u201cTowards a Holistic Understanding of the Beneficial Interactions across the ''Populus'' Microbiome.\u201d ''New Phytologist'' 205, no. 4 (March 2015): 1424\u201330. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1111/nph.13133</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1111%2Fnph.13133&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Towards%20a%20holistic%20understanding%20of%20the%20beneficial%20interactions%20across%20the%20%3Ci%3EPopulus%3C%2Fi%3E%20microbiome&rft.jtitle=New%20Phytologist&rft.stitle=New%20Phytol&rft.volume=205&rft.issue=4&rft.aufirst=St%C3%A9phane&rft.aulast=Hacquard&rft.au=St%C3%A9phane%20Hacquard&rft.au=Christopher%20W.%20Schadt&rft.date=2015-03&rft.pages=1424-1430&rft.spage=1424&rft.epage=1430&rft.issn=0028646X&rft.language=en\"></span></ref>.\n\n=== Virome ===\nAll of the viruses included in a holobiont are collectively referred to as the [[virome]]<ref>Grasis, Juris A. \u201cThe Intra-Dependence of Viruses and the Holobiont.\u201d ''Frontiers in Immunology'' 8 (November 9, 2017). <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.3389/fimmu.2017.01501</nowiki>. </ref>.\n\n=== Microbiome ===\nThe microbiome includes bacteria<ref name=\":4\" />, [[archaea]]<ref name=\":3\">Hassani, M. Amine, Paloma Dur\u00e1n, and St\u00e9phane Hacquard. \u201cMicrobial Interactions within the Plant Holobiont.\u201d ''Microbiome'' 6, no. 1 (March 27, 2018): 58. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1186/s40168-018-0445-0</nowiki>. </ref>, microscopic fungi<ref name=\":1\" />, and microscopic [[Protist|protists]]<ref name=\":3\" />. \u00a0\n\n=== Other bionts ===\nMulticellular fungi can be included in holobionts, such as [[Arbuscular mycorrhiza|arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi]] (AMF) in the roots of plants<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" />. \n\n== In corals ==\nReef-building corals are holobionts that include the coral itself (a eukaryotic [[invertebrate]] within class [[Anthozoa]]), [[Photosynthesis|photosynthetic]] [[Dinoflagellate|dinoflagellates]] called [[zooxanthellae]] (''[[Symbiodinium]]''), and associated bacteria and viruses<ref name=\":0\" />. Co-evolutionary patterns exist for coral microbial communities and coral phylogeny.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pollock|first=F. Joseph|last2=McMinds|first2=Ryan|last3=Smith|first3=Styles|last4=Bourne|first4=David G.|last5=Willis|first5=Bette L.|last6=Medina|first6=M\u00f3nica|last7=Thurber|first7=Rebecca Vega|last8=Zaneveld|first8=Jesse R.|date=2018-11-22|title=Coral-associated bacteria demonstrate phylosymbiosis and cophylogeny|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-018-07275-x|journal=Nature Communications|language=en|volume=9|issue=1|pages=1\u201313|doi=10.1038/s41467-018-07275-x|issn=2041-1723}}</ref>  \n\n== In plants ==\nThe plant holobiont is relatively well-studied, with particular focus on agricultural species such as [[Legume|legumes]] and [[Grain|grains]]. Bacteria, fungi, archaea, protists, and viruses are all members of the plant holobiont<ref name=\":3\" />.\n\nThe bacteria phyla known to be part of the plant holobiont are [[Actinobacteria]], [[Bacteroidetes]], [[Firmicutes]], and [[Proteobacteria]]<ref name=\":4\" /> . For example, [[Nitrogen fixing bacteria|nitrogen-fixers]] such as ''[[Azotobacter]]'' (Proteobacteria) and ''[[Bacillus]]'' (Firmicutes) greatly improve plant performance<ref name=\":4\" />.\n\nFungi of the phyla [[Ascomycota]], [[Basidiomycota]], and [[Glomeromycota]] colonize plant tissues and provide a variety of functions for the plant host<ref name=\":3\" />. Arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi (Glomeromycota), for instance, are common across plant groups and provide improved nutrient acquisition, temperature and drought resistance, and reduced [[pathogen]] load<ref>Begum, Naheeda, Cheng Qin, Muhammad Abass Ahanger, Sajjad Raza, Muhammad Ishfaq Khan, Muhammad Ashraf, Nadeem Ahmed, and Lixin Zhang. \u201cRole of Arbuscular Mycorrhizal Fungi in Plant Growth Regulation: Implications in Abiotic Stress Tolerance.\u201d ''Frontiers in Plant Science'' 10 (2019). <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.3389/fpls.2019.01068</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.3389%2Ffpls.2019.01068&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Role%20of%20Arbuscular%20Mycorrhizal%20Fungi%20in%20Plant%20Growth%20Regulation%3A%20Implications%20in%20Abiotic%20Stress%20Tolerance&rft.jtitle=Frontiers%20in%20Plant%20Science&rft.stitle=Front.%20Plant%20Sci.&rft.volume=10&rft.aufirst=Naheeda&rft.aulast=Begum&rft.au=Naheeda%20Begum&rft.au=Cheng%20Qin&rft.au=Muhammad%20Abass%20Ahanger&rft.au=Sajjad%20Raza&rft.au=Muhammad%20Ishfaq%20Khan&rft.au=Muhammad%20Ashraf&rft.au=Nadeem%20Ahmed&rft.au=Lixin%20Zhang&rft.date=2019&rft.issn=1664-462X&rft.language=English\"></span></ref>. ''[[Epichlo\u00eb]]'' species (Ascomycota) are part of the [[Festuca pratensis|meadow fescue]] holobiont and provide herbivore resistance by producing [[Ergoline|ergot alkaloids]], which cause [[ergotism]] in mammals<ref>Guerre, Philippe. \u201cErgot Alkaloids Produced by Endophytic Fungi of the Genus Epichlo\u00eb.\u201d ''Toxins'' 7, no. 3 (March 6, 2015): 773\u201390. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.3390/toxins7030773</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.3390%2Ftoxins7030773&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Ergot%20Alkaloids%20Produced%20by%20Endophytic%20Fungi%20of%20the%20Genus%20Epichlo%C3%AB&rft.jtitle=Toxins&rft.stitle=Toxins&rft.volume=7&rft.issue=3&rft.aufirst=Philippe&rft.aulast=Guerre&rft.au=Philippe%20Guerre&rft.date=2015-03-06&rft.pages=773-790&rft.spage=773&rft.epage=790&rft.issn=2072-6651&rft.language=en\"></span></ref>.\n\nProtist members of the plant holobiont are less well-studied, with most knowledge oriented towards pathogens. However, there are examples of [[Commensalism|commensalistic]] plant-protist associations, such as ''[[Phytomonas]]'' ([[Trypanosomatida|Trypanosomatidae]])<ref>Schwelm, Arne, Julia Badst\u00f6ber, Simon Bulman, Nicolas Desoignies, Mohammad Etemadi, Richard E. Falloon, Claire M. M. Gachon, et al. \u201cNot in Your Usual Top 10: Protists That Infect Plants and Algae.\u201d ''Molecular Plant Pathology'' 19, no. 4 (October 11, 2017): 1029\u201344. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1111/mpp.12580</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1111%2Fmpp.12580&rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F29024322&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Not%20in%20your%20usual%20Top%2010%3A%20protists%20that%20infect%20plants%20and%20algae&rft.jtitle=Molecular%20Plant%20Pathology&rft.stitle=Mol%20Plant%20Pathol&rft.volume=19&rft.issue=4&rft.aufirst=Arne&rft.aulast=Schwelm&rft.au=Arne%20Schwelm&rft.au=Julia%20Badst%C3%B6ber&rft.au=Simon%20Bulman&rft.au=Nicolas%20Desoignies&rft.au=Mohammad%20Etemadi&rft.au=Richard%20E.%20Falloon&rft.au=Claire%20M.%20M.%20Gachon&rft.au=Anne%20Legreve&rft.au=Julius%20Luke%C5%A1&rft.au=Ueli%20Merz&rft.au=Anna%20Nenarokova&rft.au=Martina%20Strittmatter&rft.au=Brooke%20K.%20Sullivan&rft.au=Sigrid%20Neuhauser&rft.date=2017-10-11&rft.pages=1029-1044&rft.spage=1029&rft.epage=1044&rft.issn=1464-6722\"></span></ref>.\n\n== Criticism ==\nSome authors reject the holobiont concept, saying it does not sufficiently encompass the intricacies of host-symbiont relationships<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moran|first=Nancy A.|last2=Sloan|first2=Daniel B.|date=2015-12-04|title=The Hologenome Concept: Helpful or Hollow?|journal=PLOS Biology|language=en|volume=13|issue=12|pages=e1002311|doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.1002311|issn=1545-7885|pmc=4670207|pmid=26636661}}</ref>. \n\n==See also==\n*[[Hologenomics]]\n*[[Hologenome theory of evolution]]\n*[[Phytobiome]]\n*[[Human microbiome]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Symbiosis]]\n", "text_old": "\n\nA '''holobiont''' is an assemblage of a [[Host (biology)|host]] and the many other species living in or around it, which together form a discrete [[ecological unit]].<ref name=\":02\">{{Cite web|url=https://mitpress.mit.edu/books/symbiosis-source-evolutionary-innovation|title=Symbiosis as a Source of Evolutionary Innovation|last=Margulis|first=Lynn|last2=Fester|first2=Ren\u00e9|date=|website=|publisher=MIT Press|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2016-08-12}}</ref> The components of a holobiont are individual species or bionts, while the combined [[genome]] of all bionts is the [[Hologenome theory of evolution|hologenome]]. The concept of the holobiont was defined by [[Lynn Margulis|Dr. Lynn Margulis]] in her 1991 book ''Symbiosis as a Source of Evolutionary Innovation''<ref name=\":02\" />. Holobionts include the host, virome, microbiome, and other members, all of which contribute in some way to the function of the whole<ref name=\":4\">Bulgarelli, Davide, Klaus Schlaeppi, Stijn Spaepen, Emiel Ver Loren van Themaat, and Paul Schulze-Lefert. \u201cStructure and Functions of the Bacterial Microbiota of Plants.\u201d ''Annual Review of Plant Biology'' 64, no. 1 (2013): 807\u201338. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1146/annurev-arplant-050312-120106</nowiki>. </ref><ref name=\":5\">{{Cite journal|last=Vandenkoornhuyse|first=Philippe|last2=Quaiser|first2=Achim|last3=Duhamel|first3=Marie|last4=Le Van|first4=Amandine|last5=Dufresne|first5=Alexis|date=2015-06-01|title=The importance of the microbiome of the plant holobiont|journal=The New Phytologist|volume=206|issue=4|pages=1196\u20131206|doi=10.1111/nph.13312|issn=1469-8137|pmid=25655016}}</ref>. Well-studied holobionts include [[Coral|reef-building corals]] and humans<ref name=\":0\" /><ref name=\":6\" />.\n\n== Definition ==\nA holobiont is a collection of species that are closely associated and have complex interactions, such as a plant species and the members of its [[Microbiota|microbiome]]<ref name=\":02\" /><ref name=\":1\">S\u00e1nchez-Ca\u00f1izares, Carmen, Beatriz Jorr\u00edn, Philip S Poole, and Andrzej Tkacz. \u201cUnderstanding the Holobiont: The Interdependence of Plants and Their Microbiome.\u201d ''Current Opinion in Microbiology'', Mobile genetic elements and HGT in prokaryotes * Microbiota, 38 (August 1, 2017): 188\u201396. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1016/j.mib.2017.07.001</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1016%2Fj.mib.2017.07.001&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Understanding%20the%20holobiont%3A%20the%20interdependence%20of%20plants%20and%20their%20microbiome&rft.jtitle=Current%20Opinion%20in%20Microbiology&rft.stitle=Current%20Opinion%20in%20Microbiology&rft.volume=38&rft.aufirst=Carmen&rft.aulast=S%C3%A1nchez-Ca%C3%B1izares&rft.au=Carmen%20S%C3%A1nchez-Ca%C3%B1izares&rft.au=Beatriz%20Jorr%C3%ADn&rft.au=Philip%20S%20Poole&rft.au=Andrzej%20Tkacz&rft.date=2017-08-01&rft.pages=188-196&rft.spage=188&rft.epage=196&rft.issn=1369-5274&rft.language=en\"></span></ref>. Each species present in a holobiont is a biont, and the genomes of all bionts taken together are the hologenome, or the \"comprehensive gene system\" of the holobiont<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite journal|last=Bordenstein|first=Seth R.|last2=Theis|first2=Kevin R.|date=2015-08-18|title=Host Biology in Light of the Microbiome: Ten Principles of Holobionts and Hologenomes|journal=PLOS Biol|volume=13|issue=8|pages=e1002226|doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.1002226|issn=1545-7885|pmc=4540581|pmid=26284777}}</ref>. A holobiont typically includes a [[eukaryote]] [[Host (biology)|host]] and all of the [[Symbiosis|symbiotic]] [[Virus|viruses]], [[bacteria]], [[Fungus|fungi]], etc. that live on or inside it<ref name=\":1\" />.\n\n== Versus Superorganism ==\nHolobionts are distinct from [[Superorganism|superorganisms]]; superorganisms consist of many individuals, sometimes of the same species, and the term is commonly applied to [[eusocial]] insects<ref>Youle, Merry, Nancy Knowlton, Forest Rohwer, Jeffrey Gordon, and David A. Relman. \u201cSuperorganisms and Holobionts: Looking for a Term for the Functional Entity Formed by a Macrobe and Its Associated Symbiotic Microbes and Viruses? The Term Is \u2018Holobiont.\u2019\u201d ''Microbe Magazine'' 8, no. 4 (April 1, 2013): 152\u201353. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1128/microbe.8.152.1</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1128%2Fmicrobe.8.152.1&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Superorganisms%20and%20Holobionts%3A%20Looking%20for%20a%20term%20for%20the%20functional%20entity%20formed%20by%20a%20macrobe%20and%20its%20associated%20symbiotic%20microbes%20and%20viruses%3F%20The%20term%20is%20%E2%80%9Cholobiont%E2%80%9D&rft.jtitle=Microbe%20Magazine&rft.volume=8&rft.issue=4&rft.aufirst=Merry&rft.aulast=Youle&rft.au=Merry%20Youle&rft.au=Nancy%20Knowlton&rft.au=Forest%20Rohwer&rft.au=Jeffrey%20Gordon&rft.au=David%20A.%20Relman&rft.date=2013-04-01&rft.pages=152-153&rft.spage=152&rft.epage=153&rft.issn=1558-7452%2C%201558-7460&rft.language=en\"></span></ref><ref>{{cite book|url=https://archive.org/details/b29809198|title=The Social Insects, Their Origin and Evolution|last1=Wheeler|first1=WM|date=1928|publisher=Harcourt Brace}}</ref>. An [[ant colony]] can be described as a superorganism, whereas an individual ant and its associated bacteria, fungi, etc. are a holobiont<ref name=\":2\" />. However, there is still some controversy surrounding these terms, and they have been used interchangeably in some publications<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite journal|last1=Kramer|first1=Peter|last2=Bressan|first2=Paola|date=2015|title=Humans as superorganisms: How microbes, viruses, imprinted genes, and other selfish entities shape our behavior|journal=Perspectives on Psychological Science|volume=10|issue=4|pages=464\u2013481|doi=10.1177/1745691615583131|issn=1745-6916|pmid=26177948|url=https://zenodo.org/record/894598}} [https://zenodo.org/record/894598#.WdntKGKCw1h Free, full text].</ref>.\n\n== Components of the Holobiont ==\n\n=== Host ===\nThe host member of a holobiont is typically a multicellular [[eukaryote]], such as a plant or human<ref name=\":2\" />. Notable hosts that are well-studied include humans<ref>Guchte, Maarten van de, Herv\u00e9 M. Blotti\u00e8re, and Jo\u00ebl Dor\u00e9. \u201cHumans as Holobionts: Implications for Prevention and Therapy.\u201d ''Microbiome'' 6, no. 1 (December 2018): 81. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1186/s40168-018-0466-8</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1186%2Fs40168-018-0466-8&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Humans%20as%20holobionts%3A%20implications%20for%20prevention%20and%20therapy&rft.jtitle=Microbiome&rft.stitle=Microbiome&rft.volume=6&rft.issue=1&rft.aufirst=Maarten&rft.aulast=van%20de%20Guchte&rft.au=Maarten%20van%20de%20Guchte&rft.au=Herv%C3%A9%20M.%20Blotti%C3%A8re&rft.au=Jo%C3%ABl%20Dor%C3%A9&rft.date=2018-12&rft.pages=81&rft.issn=2049-2618&rft.language=en\"></span></ref>, corals<ref name=\":0\">Knowlton, Nancy, and Forest Rohwer. \u201cMultispecies Microbial Mutualisms on Coral Reefs: The Host as a Habitat.\u201d ''The American Naturalist'' 162, no. 4 Suppl (October 2003): S51-62. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1086/378684</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1086%2F378684&rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F14583857&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Multispecies%20microbial%20mutualisms%20on%20coral%20reefs%3A%20the%20host%20as%20a%20habitat&rft.jtitle=The%20American%20Naturalist&rft.stitle=Am.%20Nat.&rft.volume=162&rft.issue=4%20Suppl&rft.aufirst=Nancy&rft.aulast=Knowlton&rft.au=Nancy%20Knowlton&rft.au=Forest%20Rohwer&rft.date=2003-10&rft.pages=S51-62&rft.spage=S51&rft.epage=62&rft.issn=0003-0147&rft.language=eng\"></span></ref>,  and pine trees<ref>Hacquard, St\u00e9phane, and Christopher W. Schadt. \u201cTowards a Holistic Understanding of the Beneficial Interactions across the ''Populus'' Microbiome.\u201d ''New Phytologist'' 205, no. 4 (March 2015): 1424\u201330. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1111/nph.13133</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1111%2Fnph.13133&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Towards%20a%20holistic%20understanding%20of%20the%20beneficial%20interactions%20across%20the%20%3Ci%3EPopulus%3C%2Fi%3E%20microbiome&rft.jtitle=New%20Phytologist&rft.stitle=New%20Phytol&rft.volume=205&rft.issue=4&rft.aufirst=St%C3%A9phane&rft.aulast=Hacquard&rft.au=St%C3%A9phane%20Hacquard&rft.au=Christopher%20W.%20Schadt&rft.date=2015-03&rft.pages=1424-1430&rft.spage=1424&rft.epage=1430&rft.issn=0028646X&rft.language=en\"></span></ref>.\n\n=== Virome ===\nAll of the viruses included in a holobiont are collectively referred to as the [[virome]]<ref>Grasis, Juris A. \u201cThe Intra-Dependence of Viruses and the Holobiont.\u201d ''Frontiers in Immunology'' 8 (November 9, 2017). <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.3389/fimmu.2017.01501</nowiki>. </ref>.\n\n=== Microbiome ===\nThe microbiome includes bacteria<ref name=\":4\" />, [[archaea]]<ref name=\":3\">Hassani, M. Amine, Paloma Dur\u00e1n, and St\u00e9phane Hacquard. \u201cMicrobial Interactions within the Plant Holobiont.\u201d ''Microbiome'' 6, no. 1 (March 27, 2018): 58. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1186/s40168-018-0445-0</nowiki>. </ref>, microscopic fungi<ref name=\":1\" />, and microscopic [[Protist|protists]]<ref name=\":3\" />. \u00a0\n\n=== Other bionts ===\nMulticellular fungi can be included in holobionts, such as [[Arbuscular mycorrhiza|arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi]] (AMF) in the roots of plants<ref name=\":1\" /><ref name=\":5\" />. \n\n== In corals ==\nReef-building corals are holobionts that include the coral itself (a eukaryotic [[invertebrate]] within class [[Anthozoa]]), [[Photosynthesis|photosynthetic]] [[Dinoflagellate|dinoflagellates]] called [[zooxanthellae]] (''[[Symbiodinium]]''), and associated bacteria and viruses<ref name=\":0\" />. Co-evolutionary patterns exist for coral microbial communities and coral phylogeny.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Pollock|first=F. Joseph|last2=McMinds|first2=Ryan|last3=Smith|first3=Styles|last4=Bourne|first4=David G.|last5=Willis|first5=Bette L.|last6=Medina|first6=M\u00f3nica|last7=Thurber|first7=Rebecca Vega|last8=Zaneveld|first8=Jesse R.|date=2018-11-22|title=Coral-associated bacteria demonstrate phylosymbiosis and cophylogeny|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-018-07275-x|journal=Nature Communications|language=en|volume=9|issue=1|pages=1\u201313|doi=10.1038/s41467-018-07275-x|issn=2041-1723}}</ref>  \n\n== In plants ==\nThe plant holobiont is relatively well-studied, with particular focus on agricultural species such as [[Legume|legumes]] and [[Grain|grains]]. Bacteria, fungi, archaea, protists, and viruses are all members of the plant holobiont<ref name=\":3\" />.\n\nThe bacteria phyla known to be part of the plant holobiont are [[Actinobacteria]], [[Bacteroidetes]], [[Firmicutes]], and [[Proteobacteria]]<ref name=\":4\" /> . For example, [[Nitrogen fixing bacteria|nitrogen-fixers]] such as ''[[Azotobacter]]'' (Proteobacteria) and ''[[Bacillus]]'' (Firmicutes) greatly improve plant performance<ref name=\":4\" />.\n\nFungi of the phyla [[Ascomycota]], [[Basidiomycota]], and [[Glomeromycota]] colonize plant tissues and provide a variety of functions for the plant host<ref name=\":3\" />. Arbuscular mycorrhizal fungi (Glomeromycota), for instance, are common across plant groups and provide improved nutrient acquisition, temperature and drought resistance, and reduced [[pathogen]] load<ref>Begum, Naheeda, Cheng Qin, Muhammad Abass Ahanger, Sajjad Raza, Muhammad Ishfaq Khan, Muhammad Ashraf, Nadeem Ahmed, and Lixin Zhang. \u201cRole of Arbuscular Mycorrhizal Fungi in Plant Growth Regulation: Implications in Abiotic Stress Tolerance.\u201d ''Frontiers in Plant Science'' 10 (2019). <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.3389/fpls.2019.01068</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.3389%2Ffpls.2019.01068&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Role%20of%20Arbuscular%20Mycorrhizal%20Fungi%20in%20Plant%20Growth%20Regulation%3A%20Implications%20in%20Abiotic%20Stress%20Tolerance&rft.jtitle=Frontiers%20in%20Plant%20Science&rft.stitle=Front.%20Plant%20Sci.&rft.volume=10&rft.aufirst=Naheeda&rft.aulast=Begum&rft.au=Naheeda%20Begum&rft.au=Cheng%20Qin&rft.au=Muhammad%20Abass%20Ahanger&rft.au=Sajjad%20Raza&rft.au=Muhammad%20Ishfaq%20Khan&rft.au=Muhammad%20Ashraf&rft.au=Nadeem%20Ahmed&rft.au=Lixin%20Zhang&rft.date=2019&rft.issn=1664-462X&rft.language=English\"></span></ref>. ''[[Epichlo\u00eb]]'' species (Ascomycota) are part of the [[Festuca pratensis|meadow fescue]] holobiont and provide herbivore resistance by producing [[Ergoline|ergot alkaloids]], which cause [[ergotism]] in mammals<ref>Guerre, Philippe. \u201cErgot Alkaloids Produced by Endophytic Fungi of the Genus Epichlo\u00eb.\u201d ''Toxins'' 7, no. 3 (March 6, 2015): 773\u201390. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.3390/toxins7030773</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.3390%2Ftoxins7030773&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Ergot%20Alkaloids%20Produced%20by%20Endophytic%20Fungi%20of%20the%20Genus%20Epichlo%C3%AB&rft.jtitle=Toxins&rft.stitle=Toxins&rft.volume=7&rft.issue=3&rft.aufirst=Philippe&rft.aulast=Guerre&rft.au=Philippe%20Guerre&rft.date=2015-03-06&rft.pages=773-790&rft.spage=773&rft.epage=790&rft.issn=2072-6651&rft.language=en\"></span></ref>.\n\nProtist members of the plant holobiont are less well-studied, with most knowledge oriented towards pathogens. However, there are examples of [[Commensalism|commensalistic]] plant-protist associations, such as ''[[Phytomonas]]'' ([[Trypanosomatida|Trypanosomatidae]])<ref>Schwelm, Arne, Julia Badst\u00f6ber, Simon Bulman, Nicolas Desoignies, Mohammad Etemadi, Richard E. Falloon, Claire M. M. Gachon, et al. \u201cNot in Your Usual Top 10: Protists That Infect Plants and Algae.\u201d ''Molecular Plant Pathology'' 19, no. 4 (October 11, 2017): 1029\u201344. <nowiki>https://doi.org/10.1111/mpp.12580</nowiki>.\n\n<span class=\"Z3988\" title=\"url_ver=Z39.88-2004&ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fzotero.org%3A2&rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.1111%2Fmpp.12580&rft_id=info%3Apmid%2F29024322&rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&rft.genre=article&rft.atitle=Not%20in%20your%20usual%20Top%2010%3A%20protists%20that%20infect%20plants%20and%20algae&rft.jtitle=Molecular%20Plant%20Pathology&rft.stitle=Mol%20Plant%20Pathol&rft.volume=19&rft.issue=4&rft.aufirst=Arne&rft.aulast=Schwelm&rft.au=Arne%20Schwelm&rft.au=Julia%20Badst%C3%B6ber&rft.au=Simon%20Bulman&rft.au=Nicolas%20Desoignies&rft.au=Mohammad%20Etemadi&rft.au=Richard%20E.%20Falloon&rft.au=Claire%20M.%20M.%20Gachon&rft.au=Anne%20Legreve&rft.au=Julius%20Luke%C5%A1&rft.au=Ueli%20Merz&rft.au=Anna%20Nenarokova&rft.au=Martina%20Strittmatter&rft.au=Brooke%20K.%20Sullivan&rft.au=Sigrid%20Neuhauser&rft.date=2017-10-11&rft.pages=1029-1044&rft.spage=1029&rft.epage=1044&rft.issn=1464-6722\"></span></ref>.\n\n== Criticism ==\nSome authors reject the holobiont concept, saying it does not sufficiently encompass the intricacies of host-symbiont relationships<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Moran|first=Nancy A.|last2=Sloan|first2=Daniel B.|date=2015-12-04|title=The Hologenome Concept: Helpful or Hollow?|journal=PLOS Biology|language=en|volume=13|issue=12|pages=e1002311|doi=10.1371/journal.pbio.1002311|issn=1545-7885|pmc=4670207|pmid=26636661}}</ref>. \n\n==See also==\n*[[Hologenomics]]\n*[[Hologenome theory of evolution]]\n*[[Phytobiome]]\n*[[Human microbiome]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Symbiosis]]\n", "name_user": "Epipelagic", "label": "safe", "comment": "wikilink", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Holobiont"}
{"title_page": "Jelek, Iraq", "text_new": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Jelek\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            =\n|settlement_type        = \n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Iraq\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Iraq\n|subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Iraq}}\n|subdivision_type1      = Region\n|subdivision_name1      ={{flag|Kurdistan Region}}\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Governorates of Iraq|Governorate]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Dohuk Governorate]]\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Iraq|District]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Amadiya District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = \n|subdivision_name4      =\n|leader_title           = \n|leader_name            =\n|established_title      = \n|established_date       = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|population_as_of               = 1957\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_total               =519<ref name=\"Ishtar\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,35258.html|title=Jelek (Lower and upper Jelek)|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=15 June 2011|website=[[Ishtar TV]]|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n|population_density_km2         =\n|timezone=\n|utc_offset=\n|timezone_DST=\n|utc_offset_DST=\n|coordinates            = {{coord|37.231111|43.1675|type:landmark_region:}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_ft           =\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n'''Jelek''' ({{lang-syr|\u071f\u0330\u0720\u071f}},<ref name=\"Ishtar\"/> {{lang-ku|\u00c7elk\u00ea}})<ref>{{cite news |title=Bernam\u00ea \u015filama.. Li dor r\u00eawresm\u00ean \u015faned\u00eara Gund\u00ea \u00e7elk\u00ea |url=http://waarmedia.com/latini/bername-silama-li-dor-rewresmen-sanedera-gunde-celke/ |accessdate=19 December 2019 |work=WAARmedia Kurmanc\u00ee |date=30 April 2017}}</ref> is a village in [[Dohuk Governorate]] in [[Kurdistan Region]], [[Iraq]]. It is located by the [[Khabur (Tigris)|Little Khabur]] river in the district of [[Amadiya District|Amadiya]] and the historical region of [[Barwari]].\n\nIn the village, there is a church of Mar Shmune.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,35532.html?fbclid=IwAR3Gu6lGQYMxRLcP6FQAdl0hC_HTcnwxQcY5fvOUusxJIfrocHtqNwXVv0A|title=Mar Shmune church \u2013 Jelek|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=12 October 2011|website=[[Ishtar TV]]|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nJelek was populated by 519 [[Assyrian people|Assyrians]] in 1957, with over 400 families inhabiting 200 houses.<ref name=\"Ishtar\"/> After the eruption of the [[First Iraqi\u2013Kurdish War]] in 1961, the villagers were forced to flee and could not return until the war's conclusion in 1970.<ref name=\"Ishtar\"/> However, Jelek was destroyed and its population forcibly evacuated to Bersevi, near the town of [[Zakho]], by the Iraqi army in 1979.<ref name=\"Ishtar\"/>\n\nThe construction of 62 houses, a church, hall, and school by the [[Sarkis Aghajan Mamendo#Activities|Supreme Committee of Christian Affairs]] in the 2000s heralded the return of the village's inhabitants by 2011.<ref name=\"Ishtar\"/> Jelek is largely inhabited by Assyrians.<ref name=\"Ishtar\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Dohuk Province]]\n[[Category:Assyrian communities in Iraq]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox settlement\n|name                   = Jelek\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            =\n|settlement_type        = \n|image_skyline          = \n|imagesize              = \n|image_caption          = \n|pushpin_map            = Iraq\n|pushpin_label_position = right\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location in Iraq\n|subdivision_type       = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n|subdivision_name       = {{flag|Iraq}}\n|subdivision_type1      = Region\n|subdivision_name1      ={{flag|Kurdistan Region}}\n|subdivision_type2      = [[Governorates of Iraq|Governorate]]\n|subdivision_name2      = [[Dohuk Governorate]]\n|subdivision_type3      = [[Districts of Iraq|District]]\n|subdivision_name3      = [[Amadiya District]]\n|subdivision_type4      = \n|subdivision_name4      =\n|leader_title           = \n|leader_name            =\n|established_title      = \n|established_date       = \n|area_total_km2           = \n|population_as_of               = 1957\n|population_footnotes           =\n|population_total               =519<ref name=\"Ishtar\">{{cite web |url=https://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,35258.html|title=Jelek (Lower and upper Jelek)|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=15 June 2011|website=[[Ishtar TV]]|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n|population_density_km2         =\n|timezone=\n|utc_offset=\n|timezone_DST=\n|utc_offset_DST=\n|coordinates            = {{coord|37.231111|43.1675|type:landmark_region:}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  \n|elevation_m            = \n|elevation_ft           =\n|website                = \n|footnotes              = \n}}\n'''Jelek''' ({{lang-syr|\u071f\u0330\u0720\u071f}},<ref name=\"Ishtar\"/> {{lang-ku|\u00c7elk\u00ea}})<ref>{{cite news |title=Bernam\u00ea \u015filama.. Li dor r\u00eawresm\u00ean \u015faned\u00eara Gund\u00ea \u00e7elk\u00ea |url=http://waarmedia.com/latini/bername-silama-li-dor-rewresmen-sanedera-gunde-celke/ |accessdate=19 December 2019 |work=WAARmedia Kurmanc\u00ee |date=30 April 2017}}</ref> is a village in [[Dohuk Governorate]] in [[Kurdistan Region]], [[Iraq]]. It is located by the [[Khabur (Tigris)|Little Khabur]] river in the district of [[Amadiya District|Amadiya]] and the historical region of [[Barwari]].\n\nIn the village, there is a church of Mar Shmune.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.ishtartv.com/en/viewarticle,35532.html?fbclid=IwAR3Gu6lGQYMxRLcP6FQAdl0hC_HTcnwxQcY5fvOUusxJIfrocHtqNwXVv0A|title=Mar Shmune church \u2013 Jelek|author=<!--Not stated--> |date=12 October 2011|website=[[Ishtar TV]]|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nJelek was populated by 519 [[Assyrian people]] in 1957, with over 400 families inhabiting 200 houses.<ref name=\"Ishtar\"/> After the eruption of the [[First Iraqi\u2013Kurdish War]] in 1961, the villagers were forced to flee and could not return until the war's conclusion in 1970.<ref name=\"Ishtar\"/> However, Jelek was destroyed and its population forcibly evacuated to Bersevi, near the town of [[Zakho]], by the Iraqi army in 1979.<ref name=\"Ishtar\"/>\n\nThe construction of 62 houses, a church, hall, and school by the [[Sarkis Aghajan Mamendo#Activities|Supreme Committee of Christian Affairs]] in the 2000s heralded the return of the village's inhabitants by 2011.<ref name=\"Ishtar\"/> Jelek is largely inhabited by Assyrians.<ref name=\"Ishtar\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Populated places in Dohuk Province]]\n[[Category:Assyrian communities in Iraq]]\n", "name_user": "Ashurpedia", "label": "safe", "comment": "\"Assyrians\" sounds better than \"Assyrian people\" in that sentence.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Jelek,_Iraq"}
{"title_page": "Horse Isle", "text_new": "SUB TO ALI ON YOUTUBE \n{{for|the video game|Horse Isle (video game)}}\n[[Image:HorseIsleNearArdrossan(StuartMcMahon)Jun2004.jpg|234px|right|thumb|<center>An aerial view of Horse Isle.</center>]]\n\n'''Horse Isle''' (''Gaelic - Eilean nan Each'') is an uninhabited [[island]] located in the [[Firth of Clyde]], [[Scotland]] near the seaside town of [[Ardrossan]]. It is a nature reserve, run by the [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds|RSPB]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe small, rocky island lies at {{gbmappingsmall|NS211427}}, around 1 km west of the [[North Ayrshire]] town of [[Ardrossan]]. Although no higher than {{convert|13|ft|m|0}}, it provides some shelter to [[Ardrossan]] harbour. The [[Isle of Arran|Arran]] ferry passes close to the island.\n\nTwo smaller islands, North Islet and East Islet, skirt the east coast of Horse Isle and a number of other rocks litter the sound between the island and the mainland. The 1788 survey of the Montgomery or Eglinton Estates by [[John Ainslie]] was completed in 1791 and \u0636records the name 'Robinson's Rock' off the East Islet and 'Witherow's Rock' off the West side of the main island.<ref name=\"NAS\">National Archives of Scotland. RHP35796/1-5</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ardrossan North Beach.JPG|thumb|250px|Horse Isle from Ardrossan North Beach.]] \n[[File:Lighthouse on Horse Isle.jpg|thumb|upright|left|The beacon on Horse Isle.]]\nA 52 foot tall stone beacon stands at the south end of Horse Isle marking the island for shipping. Erected in 1811, it was commissioned by Hugh, [[Hugh Montgomerie, 12th Earl of Eglinton|12th Earl of Eglinton]] on the suggestion of [[John Ross (Arctic explorer)|John Ross]].<ref>Love, D 2001 'Ayrshire Coast', Fort Publishing, Pg 47</ref> It is indicated only by the word \"landmark\" on the [[Ordnance Survey]] map.\n\nThe hazard the island continued to present to shipping is reflected in fact that in excess of 17 ships have been wrecked on or near the island including:\n* ''Minerva'', a [[brig]], on route from Dublin to Glasgow, was wrecked on a reef off Horse Isle, with the loss of five of the eight people on board, one crew, a soldier, two women and a child drowned, 18 December 1821;<ref>http://canmore.org.uk/site/218332</ref><ref name=MP271221>{{Cite news |title=Ship News |newspaper=The Morning Post |date=27 December 1821 |issue=15845 }}</ref>\n* ''Morning Star'' of Dublin, blown on to Horse Isle from the south-west during a gale, crew rescued, 1st January 1871;<ref>http://canmore.org.uk/site/298195</ref>\n* ''Brigadier'' (formerly the [[List of Empire ships (F)#Empire_Frank|Empire Frank]]), a [[tugboat|tug]], stranded on the south side of Horse Isle, 21 February 1960.<ref name=\"gaz\">{{cite web| url=http://www.scottish-places.info/features/featurefirst12005.html | title=Overview of Horse Isle| publisher=[[Gazetteer for Scotland]]| accessdate=22 December 2008}}</ref><ref>http://canmore.org.uk/site/111913</ref>\n\n==Wildlife==\nToday, Horse Isle is a [[nature reserve]], run by the [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds]] (RSPB).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rspb.org.uk/reserves/guide/h/horseisland/index.asp| title=Horse Island Reserve| publisher=[[RSPB]]| accessdate=23 December 2008}}</ref> It is designated as an [[Area of Special Protection]] (AoSP).<ref name=\"FoCF\">{{cite web| url=http://www.clydeforum.org/reports/focconf.pdf| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030523033905/http://www.clydeforum.org/reports/focconf.pdf| url-status=dead| archive-date=2003-05-23| format=PDF| title=Conference on the Ecology and Management of the Firth of Clyde - Papers| year=2001| work=Firth of Clyde Forum| accessdate=2006-10-27}}</ref> for breeding seabirds and waterfowl and winter grounds. AoSPs are created under the [[Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981]] with the aim of preventing disturbance or destruction of birds. They replaced [[Bird Sanctuary Order]]s ([[List of Acts of Parliament of the United Kingdom Parliament, 1960-1979#1967|Protection of Birds Act 1967]]).\n\nHorse Island is important for species including [[European Herring Gull|herring]] and [[lesser black backed gull]]s, and [[eider]].<ref name=\"gaz\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Scottish islands}}\n* [[List of islands of Scotland]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pNXuoq8u47c YouTube video of Horse Isle (Eilian nan Each) from Ardrossan]\n\n{{Islands of the Clyde}}\n\n{{coord|55.64482|N|4.84436|W|region:GB_source:enwiki-osgb36(NS211427)|display=title}}<!-- Note: WGS84 lat/long, converted from OSGB36 grid ref -->\n\n\n{{NorthAyrshire-geo-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of the Clyde]]\n[[Category:Uninhabited islands of North Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:Beacon towers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other places3|Horse Island (disambiguation)}}\n{{for|the video game|Horse Isle (video game)}}\n[[Image:HorseIsleNearArdrossan(StuartMcMahon)Jun2004.jpg|234px|right|thumb|<center>An aerial view of Horse Isle.</center>]]\n\n'''Horse Isle''' (''Gaelic - Eilean nan Each'') is an uninhabited [[island]] located in the [[Firth of Clyde]], [[Scotland]] near the seaside town of [[Ardrossan]]. It is a nature reserve, run by the [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds|RSPB]].\n\n==Geography==\nThe small, rocky island lies at {{gbmappingsmall|NS211427}}, around 1 km west of the [[North Ayrshire]] town of [[Ardrossan]]. Although no higher than {{convert|13|ft|m|0}}, it provides some shelter to [[Ardrossan]] harbour. The [[Isle of Arran|Arran]] ferry passes close to the island.\n\nTwo smaller islands, North Islet and East Islet, skirt the east coast of Horse Isle and a number of other rocks litter the sound between the island and the mainland. The 1788 survey of the Montgomery or Eglinton Estates by [[John Ainslie]] was completed in 1791 and records the name 'Robinson's Rock' off the East Islet and 'Witherow's Rock' off the West side of the main island.<ref name=\"NAS\">National Archives of Scotland. RHP35796/1-5</ref>\n\n==History==\n[[File:Ardrossan North Beach.JPG|thumb|250px|Horse Isle from Ardrossan North Beach.]] \n[[File:Lighthouse on Horse Isle.jpg|thumb|upright|left|The beacon on Horse Isle.]]\nA 52 foot tall stone beacon stands at the south end of Horse Isle marking the island for shipping. Erected in 1811, it was commissioned by Hugh, [[Hugh Montgomerie, 12th Earl of Eglinton|12th Earl of Eglinton]] on the suggestion of [[John Ross (Arctic explorer)|John Ross]].<ref>Love, D 2001 'Ayrshire Coast', Fort Publishing, Pg 47</ref> It is indicated only by the word \"landmark\" on the [[Ordnance Survey]] map.\n\nThe hazard the island continued to present to shipping is reflected in fact that in excess of 17 ships have been wrecked on or near the island including:\n* ''Minerva'', a [[brig]], on route from Dublin to Glasgow, was wrecked on a reef off Horse Isle, with the loss of five of the eight people on board, one crew, a soldier, two women and a child drowned, 18 December 1821;<ref>http://canmore.org.uk/site/218332</ref><ref name=MP271221>{{Cite news |title=Ship News |newspaper=The Morning Post |date=27 December 1821 |issue=15845 }}</ref>\n* ''Morning Star'' of Dublin, blown on to Horse Isle from the south-west during a gale, crew rescued, 1st January 1871;<ref>http://canmore.org.uk/site/298195</ref>\n* ''Brigadier'' (formerly the [[List of Empire ships (F)#Empire_Frank|Empire Frank]]), a [[tugboat|tug]], stranded on the south side of Horse Isle, 21 February 1960.<ref name=\"gaz\">{{cite web| url=http://www.scottish-places.info/features/featurefirst12005.html | title=Overview of Horse Isle| publisher=[[Gazetteer for Scotland]]| accessdate=22 December 2008}}</ref><ref>http://canmore.org.uk/site/111913</ref>\n\n==Wildlife==\nToday, Horse Isle is a [[nature reserve]], run by the [[Royal Society for the Protection of Birds]] (RSPB).<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.rspb.org.uk/reserves/guide/h/horseisland/index.asp| title=Horse Island Reserve| publisher=[[RSPB]]| accessdate=23 December 2008}}</ref> It is designated as an [[Area of Special Protection]] (AoSP).<ref name=\"FoCF\">{{cite web| url=http://www.clydeforum.org/reports/focconf.pdf| archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20030523033905/http://www.clydeforum.org/reports/focconf.pdf| url-status=dead| archive-date=2003-05-23| format=PDF| title=Conference on the Ecology and Management of the Firth of Clyde - Papers| year=2001| work=Firth of Clyde Forum| accessdate=2006-10-27}}</ref> for breeding seabirds and waterfowl and winter grounds. AoSPs are created under the [[Wildlife and Countryside Act 1981]] with the aim of preventing disturbance or destruction of birds. They replaced [[Bird Sanctuary Order]]s ([[List of Acts of Parliament of the United Kingdom Parliament, 1960-1979#1967|Protection of Birds Act 1967]]).\n\nHorse Island is important for species including [[European Herring Gull|herring]] and [[lesser black backed gull]]s, and [[eider]].<ref name=\"gaz\"/>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Scottish islands}}\n* [[List of islands of Scotland]]\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=pNXuoq8u47c YouTube video of Horse Isle (Eilian nan Each) from Ardrossan]\n\n{{Islands of the Clyde}}\n\n{{coord|55.64482|N|4.84436|W|region:GB_source:enwiki-osgb36(NS211427)|display=title}}<!-- Note: WGS84 lat/long, converted from OSGB36 grid ref -->\n\n\n{{NorthAyrshire-geo-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Islands of the Clyde]]\n[[Category:Uninhabited islands of North Ayrshire]]\n[[Category:Beacon towers]]\n", "name_user": "92.12.177.40", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Horse_Isle"}
{"title_page": "Lupita Jones", "text_new": "{{Spanish name|Jones|Garay}}\n{{Infobox pageant titleholder\n| name                = Lupita Jones\n| photo               = Lupita Jones.jpg\n| caption             = Jones in 2008.\n| birth_place         = {{nowrap|[[Mexicali]], [[Baja California]], [[Mexico]]}}\n| residence           = [[Mexico City]], [[Mexico]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1967|09|6|df=yes}}\n| birth_name          = Mar\u00eda Guadalupe Jones Garay\n| height              = {{convert|1.73|m|ftin|abbr=on}} \n| eye_color           = [[Eye color#Brown|Brown]]\n| hair_color          = [[Brown hair#Varieties of brown hair|Brown]]\n| nationalcompetition = [[Se\u00f1orita M\u00e9xico 1990]]<br>(Winner)<br>[[Miss Universe 1991]]<br>(Winner)\n| homepage            = \n| spouse              = {{marriage|Sim\u00f3n Charaf Medina|1993|2000|reason=div}}\n| children            = 1\n}}\n'''Mar\u00eda Guadalupe''' \"'''Lupita'''\" '''Jones Garay''' ({{IPA-es|lu\u02c8pita \u02c8\u029downs}}, {{IPA-es|\u029dons|}}; born 6 September 1967) is a Mexican actress, television producer, and beauty pageant titleholder who was crowned [[Miss Universe 1991]]. She was the first Mexican woman to win the crown.\n\nSince 1994, Jones has been the national director for Mexico at [[Miss Universe]] and is the franchise holder of [[Mexicana Universal]].\n\n==Miss Mexico==\nLupita Jones had studied business administration before Miss Universe and also did post-graduate studies in industrial administration at the [[Centro de Ense\u00f1anza T\u00e9cnica y Superior]] in her native city of Mexicali, Baja California.\n\n==Miss Universe==\nOnn September 1990, Jones won the title of [[Se\u00f1orita M\u00e9xico]] under the state of [[Baja California]].\n\nOn 17 May 1991, Jones competed against 72 contestants for the title of [[Miss Universe 1991]] in [[Las Vegas, USA]]. Jones entered the semifinals of the pageant in [[Miss Universe 1991#Preliminary scores|first place]], the only delegate with an average score  above 9. During the final telecast, Jones won every single round of competition: swimsuit, interview and evening gown. She dominated the next two rounds of competition (the Top 6 judges' questions and the Top 3 final question), and won the crown, the prizes and the prestigious title for her country.\n\n==TV producer==\nLupita Jones had studied business administration before Miss Universe and also did post-graduate studies in industrial administration at the [[Centro de Ense\u00f1anza T\u00e9cnica y Superior]] in her native city of Mexicali, Baja California.\n\nAfter finishing her reign in [[Miss Universe 1992|1992]], she created in 1994 the company Promocertamen with [[Televisa]] to produce [[Nuestra Belleza M\u00e9xico]], the official Mexican pageant responsible for choosing Mexico's representatives to [[Miss Universe]], [[Miss World]] and [[Miss International]].<ref name=\"10 claves\">{{cite web|url=http://www.sinembargo.mx/06-08-2011/20716|title=10 claves para entender el poder de Lupita Jones|date=6 August 2011|language=es|accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref> This new pageant was created when Se\u00f1orita M\u00e9xico was moved to another TV network, [[TV Azteca]].\n\nIn 1997, she attempted to launch the first male-only beauty contest, ''[[El Modelo M\u00e9xico]]'', but the show got little attention from the public.<ref name=\"10 claves\"/>\n\nIn 2001, for the ''Nuestra Belleza M\u00e9xico'' show, Lupita Jones launched the campaign ''report her'' campaign which invited the public to report beautiful women in their state. Critics attacked the campaign on discrimination charges.<ref name=\"10 claves\"/> She produced a winner at one of the 3 most well-known beauty pageants in the planet since 1960: [[Priscila Perales]], [[Miss International 2007]] and another one in 2009 with [[Anagabriela Espinoza]], [[Miss International 2009]]. In 2010, a Mexican woman was crowned as [[Miss Universe 2010]], [[Ximena Navarrete]]. Accordingly, Jones promised she would vacate the direction of ''Nuestra Belleza M\u00e9xico'' once a new Mexican Miss Universe would be entitled, but did not follow through after  Navarrete won the title.<ref name=\"10 claves\"/>\n\nFrom 2008 to 2014, Lupita Jones and longtime pageant director-rival [[Osmel Sousa]] were brought together to judge Nuestra Belleza Latina, a beauty pageant-related reality television series created by the US Hispanic network [[Univision]], which searches for young women of Latin American descent across the [[United States]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.elnuevodia.com/entretenimiento/tv/nota/lupitajonesrenunciaanuestrabellezalatina-1851110/|title=Lupita Jones renuncia a Nuestra Belleza Latina|website=Elnuevodia.com|date=9 September 2014|language=es|accessdate=13 September 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2015, in response to negative comments on Mexicans by [[Donald Trump]], part-owner of the Miss Universe organization, as head of Nuestra Belleza M\u00e9xico, Jones endorsed withdrawal of the 2015 contestant from Mexico and urged a boycott of products associated with the 2015 pageant.<ref>{{cite news\n|url = http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-3145436/Donald-Trump-comes-fighting-prime-time-Tycoon-says-controversial-comments-Mexicans-rapists-totally-accurate-Univision-no-right-cancel-Miss-USA.html \n|title = Donald Trump comes out fighting on prime time: Tycoon says his controversial comments on Mexican 'rapists' were 'totally accurate' and Univision had no right to cancel Miss USA broadcast \n|date = 2015-07-04 \n|accessdate = 2015-07-03 \n|newspaper = Daily Mail\n|first1 =  Chris \n|last1 = Spargo\n|first2 = Christopher  \n|last2 = Brennan\n}}</ref>\n\n==Humanitarian causes==\nIn 1999, Lupita Jones decided that the contest would support an important program for ill-treated girls in the country through the [[Desarrollo Integral de la Familia|Integral Family Development]] project.\n\nIn 2000, Jones accepted an appointment as [[UNFPA]] [[UNFPA Goodwill Ambassador|Goodwill Ambassador]] and Face to Face Campaign Spokesperson for Mexico.<ref name=\"10 claves\"/>\n\n==Private life==\nLupita Jones has one son from her previous union with former spouse, Sim\u00f3n Charaf.\n\n==Filmography==\n\n;Telenovelas\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Project !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2017 || ''[[Enamor\u00e1ndome de Ram\u00f3n]]'' || Katy Fern\u00e1ndez de Medina || Special participation\n|-\n| 2015 || ''[[Como dice el dicho]]'' || Roc\u00edo / Ana Regina  || 2 Episodes\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[La malquerida (telenovela)]]'' || Carmen Gallardo de Torres || rowspan=2|Recurring role\n|-\n| 2013 || ''[[Rosario (American telenovela)|Rosario]]'' || Fabiana\n|-\n|}\n\n==Books==\n*{{cite book |last= |first= |date=1993 |title=Palabra de reina |trans-title= |url=https://archive.org/details/palabradereina00jone |language=es |location= |publisher=Grupo Editorial Planeta |isbn=978-9684063037 }}\n*{{cite book |last= |first= |date=2006 |title=Bella y en forma, 15 anos despues |trans-title= |url= |language=es |location= |publisher=Planeta |isbn=978-9703705634}}\n*{{cite book |last= |first= |date=2011 |title=Deten el tiempo |trans-title= |url= |language=es |location= |publisher=Urano |isbn=978-8479537852}}\n*{{cite book |last= |first= |date=2012 |title=ABC para rejuvenecer |trans-title= |url=https://archive.org/details/elabcpararejuven0000jone |language=es |location= |publisher=Urano |isbn=978-6077835462 }}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{IMDb name|1620682}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20130925075702/http://www.missuniverse.com/contestant_profiles/past Miss Universe Official Website]\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach}}\n{{s-bef|before={{flagicon|Norway}} [[Mona Grudt]]|}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Miss Universe]]\n|years=[[Miss Universe 1991|1991]]}}\n{{s-aft|after={{flagicon|Namibia}} [[Michelle McLean]]}}\n{{s-bef|before=Maril\u00e9 del Rosario|}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Miss Mexico Organization|Miss Mexico]]\n|years=[[Se\u00f1orita M\u00e9xico#Winners|1990]]}}\n{